"'''Tired and emotional'''" is a [[euphemism]] for "drunk." It was coined by the [[United Kingdom|British]] [[satire|satirical]] magazine ''[[Private Eye]]'' in [[1967]] in reference to [[Labour Party (UK)|Labour]] Cabinet minister [[George Brown, Baron George-Brown|George Brown]], but is now used as a stock phrase; the law of [[libel]] makes it unwise ever to directly refer to someone as drunk. Its use has extended well beyond the magazine.

